9 III. Institutions of higher education located in New Hampshire may assist in the
10 preparation of training aids derived from human remains for law enforcement purposes, provided
11 that:
12 (a) The institution employs or contracts with a properly trained and credentialed
13 medical professional, including a doctor of philosophy (Ph.D.) in a relevant anatomical or forensic
14 science field, a doctor of osteopathic medicine (D.O.), or a doctor of medicine (M.D.), who shall
15 overseethepreparationprocess.
16 (b) The preparation of the training aid occurs on-site at a licensed funeral home or
17 mortuary, with the consent of the funeral director and in accordance with all applicable health and
18 safetyregulations.
19 (c) The institution maintains a written agreement with the law enforcement agency
20 requesting the training aid, outlining the scope of work, handling procedures, and chain of custody
21 fortheremains.
22 (d) All activities are conducted in compliance with the consent requirements outlined in
23 RSA291-B:2,IandII.
24 291-B:4 Agency Policy Requirements. Any law enforcement agency in New Hampshire that
25 conducts training involving the possession or use of human remains for cadaver canine or related
26 law enforcement purposes shall develop and maintain a written policy governing such activities.
27 This policy shall be submitted to and kept on file with the New Hampshire police standards and
28 trainingcouncil. Thepolicyshallinclude,ataminimum:
29 I. A detailed acquisition plan outlining the lawful and ethical process for obtaining human
30 remains,includingdocumentationofconsentasrequiredunderRSA291-B:2.
31 II. A handling, storage, and documentation plan that ensures the secure, respectful, and
32 traceablemanagementofhumanremainsthroughoutthetrainingprocess.
33 III. A destruction or final disposition plan that complies with RSA 291-B:3 and applicable
34 state and federal regulations, including procedures for returning remains to an authorized
35 institutionorlicensedmedicalwastedisposalprovider.
